<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{kotonisuru}}</strong> indicates a volitional decision. It is a more complex form of
<a href="grammar-ni-suru.html">@N{{}}@HI{{nisuru}}</a>, where the noun is replaced with a nominalised phrase.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{capital^metropolis}}made@KT{{basu}}de@KJ{{going}}ku<strong>kotonishimashou</strong.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Let's go as far as Kyoto by bus.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{every^day^Sino-^character}}wo@KJ{{ten}}@KJ{{memorize}}eru<strong>kotonishimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I've decided to memorise ten kanji every day.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
The form <strong>@HI{{kotonishiteiru}}</strong> indicates that the decision is still in force.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{meat}}woamari@KJ{{eat}}nai<strong>kotonishiteiru</strong.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I make it a rule not to eat very much meat.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

